Pages = {325-340},
Month = {JUL},
Abstract = {In any procedural mathematical situation, there are multiple ways of
   achieving the same answer. Given this observation, we ask, why choose
   one procedural solution over another? We address this question here with
   data drawn from interviews conducted with university students engaged in
   row-reducing matrices. During their tasks, the students voiced a variety
   of justifications for the procedural steps they enacted. Through a
   phenomenographical analysis (Marton, Instructional Science, 10, 177-200,
   1981) of their utterances, we construct a framework for justifications
   for choices made within procedures with two broad categories,
   algorithmic and anticipatory. By comparison, this is similar to the
   creative/imitative reasoning framework of Lithner (Educational Studies
   in Mathematics, 67, 255-276, 2008), a framework primarily emerging from
   less procedural settings. We suggest that, given this richness in
   justifications brought forth by a procedural setting, when used
   effectively, instruction in mathematical procedures has the potential to
   contribute to deeper, more flexible forms of mathematical knowledge
   overall.},
