Abstract = {There is broad acceptance that mathematics teachers' beliefs about the
   nature of mathematics influence the ways in which they teach the
   subject. It is also recognised that mathematics as practised in typical
   school classrooms is different from the mathematical activity of
   mathematicians. This paper presents case studies of two secondary
   mathematics teachers, one experienced and the other relatively new to
   teaching, and considers their beliefs about the nature of mathematics,
   as a discipline and as a school subject. Possible origins and future
   developments of the structures of their belief systems are discussed
   along with implications of such structures for their practice. It is
   suggested that beliefs about mathematics can usefully be considered in
   terms of a matrix that accommodates the possibility of differing views
   of school mathematics and the discipline.},
