Abstract = {Mathematicians frequently attend their peers' lectures to learn new
   mathematical content. The goal of this paper is to investigate what
   mathematicians learned from the lectures. Our research took place at a
   2-week workshop on inner model theory, a topic of set theory, which was
   largely comprised of a series of lectures. We asked the six workshop
   organizers and seven conference attendees what could be learned from the
   lectures in the workshop, and from mathematics lectures in general. A
   key finding was that participants felt the motivation and road maps that
   were provided by the lecturers could facilitate the attendees' future
   individual studying of the material. We conclude by discussing how our
   findings inform the development of theory on how individuals can learn
   from lectures and suggest interesting directions for future research.},
