Abstract = {There is a longstanding conversation in the mathematics education
   literature about proofs that explain versus proofs that only convince.
   In this essay, we offer a characterization of explanatory proofs with
   three goals in mind. We first propose a theory of explanatory proofs for
   mathematics education in terms of representation systems. Then, we
   illustrate these ideas in terms of combinatorial proofs, focusing on
   binomial identities. Finally, we leverage our theory to explain
   audience-dependent and audience-invariant aspects of explanatory proof.
   Throughout, we use the context of combinatorics to emphasize points and
   to offer examples of proofs that can be explanatory or only convincing,
   depending on how one understands the claim being made.},
