Abstract = {What do ethical relations look like in the context of the many
   injustices that pervade mathematics education? In this paper, I argue,
   first, that violence is the relation that characterizes much of
   contemporary mathematics education and, second, that understanding
   ethical relations requires considering mathematics as an equal actor in
   creating possible relations rather than simply treating it as a context
   for human relations. I examine how literature in care theory,
   emancipatory pedagogies, and mathematics education have framed ethical
   relationality and suggest that the feminist new materialist
   conceptualization of response-ability offers several contributions for
   rethinking agency, justice, and praxis for mathematics teachers
   concerned with addressing mathematical violence.},
