Abstract = {Spontaneous gesture produced in conjunction with speech is considered as
   both a source of data about mathematical thinking, and as an integral
   modality in communication and cognition. The analysis draws on a corpus
   of more than 200 gestures collected during 3 h of interviews with
   prospective elementary school teachers on the topic of fractions. The
   analysis examines how gestures express meaning, utilizing the framework
   of cognitive linguistics to argue that gestures are both composed of,
   and provide inputs to, conceptual blends for mathematical ideas, and a
   standard typology drawn from gesture studies is extended to address the
   function of gestures within mathematics more appropriately.},
