Month = {OCT},
Abstract = {The COVID-19 pandemic brought with it a new way of being in a changed
   and uncertain world. Aotearoa/New Zealand took a well-being approach and
   in turn, we share the positive outcomes which resulted for some low
   socio-economic schools and communities in relation to teacher learning
   and relationships with families. In this article, we report on how
   teachers and schools connected with diverse students and their families
   during the period of remote learning. We draw on the responses from 20
   teachers and school leaders who participated in interviews. Following
   the wider government focus, schools took a well-being first approach
   which led to increased connections and positive home/school
   relationships. The results highlight how a disruptive event such as
   COVID-19 can also be a time to focus on strengths of diverse communities
   and gain insights. We demonstrate that while focusing on mathematics,
   teachers and school leaders gained insights related to their students'
   funds of knowledge and saw opportunities for learning for students,
   parents, and the teachers themselves.},
